w guidelines urging people to avoid social gatherings of more than ten people and to restrict discretionary travel. He stopped short of ordering a [[quarantine]] or a [[curfew]], but he said restrictions may last until July or August. He acknowledged that the country may be headed for a [[recession]]. Despite the fact that the [[Federal Reserve Bank]] lowered interest rates the day prior, the stock market fell once again.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/03/16/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-toll-rises-cases-testing/5053816002/ Coronavirus live updates: Guidelines call for no groups bigger than 10; Trump says restrictions could last into August] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318042652/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/03/16/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-toll-rises-cases-testing/5053816002/ |date=March 18, 2020 }} by John Bacon & Jorge L. Ortiz, USA Today, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n* Colorado: Colorado announced 29 new positive cases of COVID-19, bringing the state total to 160.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/16/polis-considering-statewide-closure-of-bars-restaurants-gyms-and-theaters/ |title=Polis Orders Statewide Closure of Seating at Bars, Restaurants |last=Markus |first=Ben |website=Colorado Public Radio |access-date=2020-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041907/https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/16/polis-considering-statewide-closure-of-bars-restaurants-gyms-and-theaters/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Michael Hancock (Colorado politician)|Mayor Hancock]] of [[Denver]] orders all bars and restaurants close by 8AM, March 17 (excepting food delivery and pickup) and also bans gatherings of more than 50 people in the city.<ref name=\"CO_mar16\">{{Cite news |last=Oravetz |first=Janet |url=https://www.9news.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/denver-coronavirus-update/73-e04fa1e5-bf55-443a-83ed-6fb3e9d02dcc |title=All Denver restaurants and bars ordered to close to indoor dining for 8 weeks |access-date=16 March 2020 |publisher=NBC - 9News}}</ref> [[Jared Polis|Governor Polis]] expanded the closures by ordering a state-wide closure of dine-in services. Polis also ordered the closure of gyms, casinos, and theaters.<ref name=\"CO_mar16_polis\">{{Cite news |last=Wingerter |first=Meg |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-colorado-bars-restaurants-dmv-closed/ |title=Colorado governor orders bars, restaurants to halt dine-in service statewide in fight against coronavirus |access-date=17 March 2020 |publisher=The Denver Post |agency=The Denver Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041906/https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-colorado-bars-restaurants-dmv-closed/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* District of Columbia: The [[Supreme Court of the United States]] postponed oral arguments scheduled for late March and April 1. Similar precautions were taken in 1918 in response to the [[Spanish flu]] and in 1798 and [[1793 Philadelphia yellow fever epidemic|1793]] in response to [[Yellow fever]] outbreaks. 18 cases of coronavirus have been reported in DC.<ref>[https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/487774-supreme-court-postpones-oral-arguments-amid-coronavirus-pandemic Supreme Court postpones oral arguments amid coronavirus pandemic] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041906/https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/487774-supreme-court-postpones-oral-arguments-amid-coronavirus-pandemic |date=March 18, 2020 }} The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n*California:  As of 12:01 AM Monday, March 16, Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti ordered all bars, movie theaters, gyms and fitness centers closed, and for restaurants to limit themselves to take-out and delivery only.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2020-03-15/coronavirus-close-los-angeles-restaurants L.A. bars forced to close, restaurants go takeout-only: \u2018Some of these closures might be permanent\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318014215/https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2020-03-15/coronavirus-close-los-angeles-restaurants |date=March 18, 2020 }}, Los Angeles Times, 16 March 2020.</ref>\n* Minnesota: The Georgia Department of Health announces there are 54 cases of the virus in the state, out of at least 1,893 tested. Several clinics, including Mayo and [[M Health Fairview]] are reporting only positive tests, not the total number of tests.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |title=Situation Update for Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309021508/https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bringmethenews.com\">{{cite web |url=https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-news/minnesotas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-54 |title=Minnesota's confirmed coronavirus cases rise to 54 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317145512/https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-news/minnesotas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-54 |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Affected counties now include Anoka, [[Benton County, MN|Benton]], [[Blue Earth County, MN|Blue Earth]], Carver, Dakota, Hennepin, [[Olmsted County, MN|Olmsted]], [[Ramsey County, MN|Ramsey]], [[Renville County, MN|Renville]], Stearns, [[Sherburne County, MN|Sherburne]], [[Waseca County, MN|Waseca]], [[Washington County, MN|Washington]], and [[Wright County, MN|Wright]].<ref name=\"bringmethenews.com\" /> Governor Tim Walz has ordered the closure of public places, including all: restaurants, bars, coffee shops, gyms, theaters, breweries, ski resorts, and other public places until at least March 27. Bars and restaurants in the state were closed only to dine in customers; the businesses were allowed to continue to serve customers by take out or delivery orders. He said this order may be extended.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |title=Walz temporarily closes bars, restaurants and gyms to curb COVID-19 spread |last=MPR Staff |website=Minnesota Public Radio |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317231710/https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Ohio: The state has 50 confirmed cases of COVID-19. Bowling alleys, fitness centers, gyms, movie theaters, public recreation centers, trampoline parks, and water parks are ordered to be shut<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200316/coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-closes-gyms-recreation-centers |title=Coronavirus: Gov. Mike DeWine closes gyms, recreation centers |last=Wagner |first=Mike |date=March 16, 2020 |website=dispatch.com |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318061227/https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200316/coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-closes-gyms-recreation-centers |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and gatherings of more than 50 people are banned.<ref name=\"CBS10 TIMELINE\"/> DeWine announces the [[United States presidential primary|presidential primary elections]], scheduled for the next day, will be cancelled on orders of Department of Health director Amy Acton.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/politics/primary-elections-coronavirus/index.html |title=States move forward with Tuesday elections as coronavirus pandemic alters American life |last=Gallagher |first=Dianne |last2=Kirkland |first2=Pamela |website=CNN |access-date=17 March 2020 |last3=Sullivan |first3=Kate |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317193715/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/politics/primary-elections-coronavirus/index.html |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Oklahoma: Governor Stitt declares a state of emergency after being criticized for ignoring social distancing. Ten cases of coronavirus are confirmed in the state.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/15/politics/oklahoma-governor-deleted-tweet-coronavirus/index.html Oklahoma governor who faced backlash over 'packed' restaurant tweet now declares state of emergency] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318053644/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/15/politics/oklahoma-governor-deleted-tweet-coronavirus/index.html |date=March 18, 2020 }} CNN, 16 Mar 2020</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://kfor.com/health/coronavirus/oklahoma-coronavirus-cases-jump-to-10-dozens-of-tests-pending/ |title=Oklahoma coronavirus cases jump to 10, dozens of tests pending |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041905/https://kfor.com/health/coronavirus/oklahoma-coronavirus-cases-jump-to-10-dozens-of-tests-pending/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Oregon: Oregon Governor Kate Brown and public health officials issue new statewide mandates, banning all public gatherings of 25 or more people and restricting restaurants to take-out or delivery service.  Only.essential businesses such as grocery stores, pharmacies, retail stores and workplaces are exempted.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kezi.com/content/news/COVID-19-cases-in-Oregon-a-timeline-of-events-568939071.html|title=Coronavirus in Oregon: A timeline of events|website=KEZI News}}</ref>\n*Pennsylvania: Governor Tom Wolf extended a shutdown order to the entire state. The order was originally for four southeastern Pennsylvania counties outside of [[Philadelphia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-pennsylvania-health-officials-76-cases/|title=Coronavirus Update: Gov. Wolf Orders Shutdown Across Pa. As Number Of COVID-19 Cases Climbs To 76, Including 2-Year-Old Montgomery County Girl|date=2020-03-16|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317162251/https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-pennsylvania-health-officials-76-cases/|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Vermont: Public schools began a transition in which student attendance was optional Monday, March 16 and Tuesday, March 17, but faculty and staff were expected to attend to help with an orderly shut down, with schools tentatively to reopen April 7. Plans were being made to continue providing special needs services and meals for those students who depend on them.<ref>[https://www.manchesterjournal.com/stories/vermont-schools-to-close,600013 Vermont schools to close], Manchester Journal, Chris Mays (Battleboro Reformer), March 15, 2020.</ref>\n* Texas:  The first death from the coronavirus occurred in [[Matagorda County, Texas|Matagorda County]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.khou.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/matagorda-county-man-becomes-first-coronavirus-related-death-in-texas/285-3be6c0f8-c4e2-4e22-882c-c5ede08dd968 |title=Matagorda County man becomes first coronavirus-related death in Texas |language=en |access-date=2020-03-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041906/https://www.khou.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/matagorda-county-man-becomes-first-coronavirus-related-death-in-texas/285-3be6c0f8-c4e2-4e22-882c-c5ede08dd968 |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Washington (state): [[Boeing]] announces it plans to build airplanes and will enhance cleaning procedures in workspaces, common areas and on [[high-touch]] surfaces in its assembly plants. The company also has a plant in South Carolina.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-16-20-intl-hnk/h_6e1f01640b115ad8c8c625f496fd06a5?fbclid=IwAR34M94sJN_64OBSI90MNjOkjhlJMxMX6c69pUluy-BwjnGaOr_fO1Vgx6A Boeing asks employees to work from home, but says it will still build planes] by Chris Isidore, CNN, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n====March 17====\n5,145 people in the United States have been infected; at least 91 have died.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/17/us-coronavirus-cases-surpass-5000-up-fivefold-from-a-week-ago.html |title=US coronavirus cases surpass 5,000, up fivefold from a week ago |last=Feuer |first=William |date=17 March 2020 |website=cnbc.com |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041705/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/17/us-coronavirus-cases-surpass-5000-up-fivefold-from-a-week-ago.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Peace Corps]] fires all 7,300 volunteers in 61 countries.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-peace-corps-isnt-just-bringing-home-7300-volunteers-because-of-the-coronavirus-its-firing-them/2020/03/20/69aa08f4-6ac0-11ea-b5f1-a5a804158597_story.html?fbclid=IwAR2V2O_UEkvaRLs1bUEK9ydswZ-AqMbB-qPUtREkeUI0FyjEfu5qqbPcYlg The Peace Corps isn't just bringing home 7,300 volunteers because of the coronavirus. It's firing them.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320225745/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-peace-corps-isnt-just-bringing-home-7300-volunteers-because-of-the-coronavirus-its-firing-them/2020/03/20/69aa08f4-6ac0-11ea-b5f1-a5a804158597_story.html%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR2V2O_UEkvaRLs1bUEK9ydswZ-AqMbB-qPUtREkeUI0FyjEfu5qqbPcYlg |date=March 20, 2020 }} by Joe Davidson, The Washington Post, 20 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n* Alabama: Alabama had a total of 39 cases, where the majority of them (21 cases) are located in Jefferson County.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fox10tv.com/news/coronavirus/alabama-now-up-to-confirmed-covid--cases/article_b0358ace-688f-11ea-8f19-0b5121c61b5b.html|title=Alabama now up to 39 confirmed COVID-19 cases|website=FOX10 News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318070159/https://www.fox10tv.com/news/coronavirus/alabama-now-up-to-conf